00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:04.290
oh, I'm going to do a demo.

00:03:04.290 --> 00:03:07.310
Apriori, a demo isn't active.

00:03:07.310 --> 00:03:08.650
I mean, it's active for you.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:10.470
You're doing the demo.

00:03:10.470 --> 00:03:13.510
But it's not necessarily
active for students.

00:03:13.510 --> 00:03:16.290
And if we enter into the
enterprise of doing a demo

00:03:16.290 --> 00:03:17.450
thinking we're being--

00:03:17.450 --> 00:03:19.860
well, thinking
they're being active--

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:21.390
they might not be.

00:03:21.390 --> 00:03:26.130
And Croutch and Mazur did
an interesting study where

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:29.430
they looked at-- they were doing
a freshmen mechanics class.

00:03:29.430 --> 00:03:32.310
And they had amasses
on an air track, when

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:34.890
you have like a massive
2M, and you slam into it

00:03:34.890 --> 00:03:37.650
with a mass of M. What
happens to the mass of 2M?

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:40.800
What happens to this mass
of M that was coming in,

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:41.850
that kind of stuff.

00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:44.324
And so that it would show
the students these demos.

00:03:44.324 --> 00:03:45.240
Oh, look what happens.

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:48.390
Here comes a mass of M at
a velocity, da, da, da.

00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:50.820
And then when they
asked students

00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:53.460
in the same class at the
end of the same class period

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:55.140
to say what happens
when a mass of M

00:03:55.140 --> 00:04:00.600
collides with a mass of 2M, a
mass of M going x miles an hour

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:04.710
collides with the mass 2M, what
happens, students got it wrong.

00:04:04.710 --> 00:04:07.280
They had just seen the demo.

00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:09.044
They had just seen the demo.

00:04:09.044 --> 00:04:10.210
And they still got it wrong.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.240
And I think that's a
really profound finding.

00:04:18.240 --> 00:04:20.246
Because as experts,
we think, of course,

00:04:20.246 --> 00:04:21.329
they're going to see this.

00:04:21.329 --> 00:04:24.180
It's going to be emblazoned
into their brain.

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:26.310
They'll never forget it.

00:04:26.310 --> 00:04:29.880
But they never
learn it, basically.

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:32.560
So it's more evidence for
active learning for sure.

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:35.460
But what they found out
was they forced students

00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:39.270
to make a prediction, to discuss
that prediction with somebody

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:42.960
else before they saw the demo.

00:04:42.960 --> 00:04:45.450
And when they did
that, the scores

00:04:45.450 --> 00:04:50.280
on these sort of post-demo
quizzes, if you will,

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:52.050
went way up.

00:04:52.050 --> 00:04:55.380
So it's a small tweak,
but it's a profound one.

00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:57.750
Because you might really
just be wasting your time

00:04:57.750 --> 00:04:59.190
if you show a lot
of demos and you

00:04:59.190 --> 00:05:02.520
don't ask students to make
these predictions beforehand.

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:04.620
This goes back to
the mathematician

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:08.730
George Polya, who wrote in
the '50s about asking people

00:05:08.730 --> 00:05:11.790
to make predictions before
you gave them the answer.

00:05:11.790 --> 00:05:13.290
I'm not sure he had
any data for it.

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:15.480
But this was his thing.

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:18.270
This is pretty good data
suggesting that you really

00:05:18.270 --> 00:05:21.090
should ask students
to make predictions

00:05:21.090 --> 00:05:22.650
before showing the demo.

