Or are you doing it
because it's really

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:23.265
going to help student
learning, or it's

00:13:23.265 --> 00:13:25.440
going to help advance
the learning outcome?

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:30.160
We can use
educational technology

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:32.950
as some kind of a scapegoat,
but that's true for anything.

00:13:32.950 --> 00:13:35.350
It's true for that
amazing exam question

00:13:35.350 --> 00:13:37.220
that you thought
up in the shower.

00:13:37.220 --> 00:13:39.210
Like, I know what I'll do.

00:13:39.210 --> 00:13:41.920
They'll do this, and do
that, and blah, blah.

00:13:41.920 --> 00:13:45.490
Maybe it's cool, but maybe it's
not going to get you anywhere.

00:13:45.490 --> 00:13:47.830
Maybe it's not consistent
with your learning outcomes.

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:49.330
So it doesn't have
to be technology.

00:13:49.330 --> 00:13:51.970
But often, technology
is kind of pretty shiny.

00:13:51.970 --> 00:13:55.240
And we tend to
gravitate toward it.

00:13:55.240 --> 00:13:57.100
But it's remembering
that we're using

00:13:57.100 --> 00:14:01.750
it to advance some particular
learning outcome, OK?

00:14:01.750 --> 00:14:05.750
So you guys did the readings.

00:14:05.750 --> 00:14:07.920
What are educational
technologies?

00:14:07.920 --> 00:14:09.890
What does it mean?

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:11.833
Can we come up
with a definition?

00:14:11.833 --> 00:14:12.735
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:14:12.735 --> 00:14:18.110
I think from what
I can understand,

00:14:18.110 --> 00:14:27.590
educational technology is a
tool which, perhaps, the student

00:14:27.590 --> 00:14:30.720
and also have the teacher.

00:14:30.720 --> 00:14:34.710
So that means something that
can enable inter-communication

00:14:34.710 --> 00:14:37.152
between the teacher
and the student.

00:14:37.152 --> 00:14:39.000
And then the student
and the student.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:43.190
PROFESSOR: OK, so we have a
lot of ideas in that statement.

00:14:43.190 --> 00:14:43.900
So it's a tool.

00:14:53.650 --> 00:14:55.546
You said, it enables
communication.

00:14:55.546 --> 00:14:58.382
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
students connect.

00:14:58.382 --> 00:15:01.334
And then the
teacher [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:23.760
PROFESSOR: And I think you
had something else in there.

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:24.260
Did you?

00:15:24.260 --> 00:15:24.760
Or no?

00:15:33.139 --> 00:15:34.150
Somebody else?

00:15:34.150 --> 00:15:36.154
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:15:36.154 --> 00:15:39.257
AUDIENCE: Education
technology is like a tool

00:15:39.257 --> 00:15:41.590
to enhance students' learning--
enhancement of student's

00:15:41.590 --> 00:15:43.813
learning.

00:15:43.813 --> 00:15:48.992
And enhancement of
instructors' teaching as well.

00:15:57.805 --> 00:16:01.582
AUDIENCE: The technology part
is like a electronic device.

00:16:01.582 --> 00:16:03.290
PROFESSOR: So it has
to have electricity?

00:16:06.110 --> 00:16:07.290
It has to involve electrons?

00:16:07.290 --> 00:16:09.940
No, that's everything.

00:16:09.940 --> 00:16:12.790
Wait, let's let Michelle--
what should we say about that?

00:16:18.257 --> 00:16:20.245
AUDIENCE: I think that's
kind of correct to say

00:16:20.245 --> 00:16:22.090
it has to be an
electronic device, right?

00:16:22.090 --> 00:16:25.030
Like if it's a
clicker or if it's a--

00:16:25.030 --> 00:16:26.510
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:16:31.980 --> 00:16:33.550
PROFESSOR: It must
be electronic.

00:16:33.550 --> 00:16:37.080
That sounds so like 1950s.

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:39.839
I think we had-- yeah, Gordon?

00:16:39.839 --> 00:16:42.304
AUDIENCE: I would just
adjust it a little bit

00:16:42.304 --> 00:16:45.262
and add in front of
the two [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:04.462
AUDIENCE: A kind of tool
that's created [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:04.462 --> 00:17:06.824
by time or place.

00:17:06.824 --> 00:17:11.450
PROFESSOR: So it lends
itself to asynchronicity?

00:17:11.450 --> 00:17:13.748
AUDIENCE: Yes,
something like that.

00:17:13.748 --> 00:17:31.952
PROFESSOR: Most-- Anything else?

00:17:31.952 --> 00:17:38.770
AUDIENCE: I think it's
also enhancer, easier

00:17:38.770 --> 00:17:42.190
use of materials.

00:17:42.190 --> 00:17:43.286
PROFESSOR: Facilitates--

00:17:46.202 --> 00:17:49.320
AUDIENCE: Yeah, materials like.

00:17:49.320 --> 00:17:51.470
It has to [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:55.375 --> 00:17:56.750
PROFESSOR: Right,
a distribution,

00:17:56.750 --> 00:17:59.153
aids distribution?

00:17:59.153 --> 00:18:13.550
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:13.550 --> 00:18:15.881
PROFESSOR: Did I
hear something else?

00:18:15.881 --> 00:18:19.110
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:19.110 --> 00:18:22.421
PROFESSOR: Efficient,
that's a loaded word.

00:18:33.616 --> 00:18:34.740
Anybody have anything else?

00:18:34.740 --> 00:18:38.220
Or does somebody want to make
a comment on this collection

00:18:38.220 --> 00:18:39.332
of attributes?

00:18:39.332 --> 00:18:40.775
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:47.074 --> 00:18:49.240
PROFESSOR: I don't think I
have any cynics in this--

00:18:49.240 --> 00:18:52.150
well, the cynics
haven't said anything.

00:18:52.150 --> 00:18:54.557
AUDIENCE: I think all the
comments are positive things.

00:18:54.557 --> 00:18:57.360
Like if you're doing it
well what should happen.

00:18:57.360 --> 00:19:00.610
But they aren't necessarily
what actually happens.

00:19:00.610 --> 00:19:04.620
Because most of the time,
it's probably not done well.

00:19:04.620 --> 00:19:07.786
Using technology is not optimal.

00:19:12.157 --> 00:19:13.740
PROFESSOR: OK, that's
one observation.

00:19:13.740 --> 00:19:16.020
It's sort of, you
know, that rhyme, there

00:19:16.020 --> 00:19:17.310
was a little girl who
had a little curl right

00:19:17.310 --> 00:19:18.060
in the middle her forehead.

00:19:18.060 --> 00:19:19.710
And when she was good,
she was very, very good.

00:19:19.710 --> 00:19:21.510
And when she was
bad, she was horrid.

00:19:21.510 --> 00:19:23.790
So it's a little bit
like this, right?

00:19:23.790 --> 00:19:25.394
When it's good, it's
very, very good.

00:19:25.394 --> 00:19:27.060
And when it's bad,
maybe it's even worse

00:19:27.060 --> 00:19:28.580
than if you hadn't bothered.

00:19:28.580 --> 00:19:32.050
But-- Alex, you had
something to say?

00:19:32.050 --> 00:19:32.660
No?

00:19:32.660 --> 00:19:34.410
AUDIENCE: Well, on the
side of the cynics,

00:19:34.410 --> 00:19:36.750
I thought that students
are often disinterested

00:19:36.750 --> 00:19:38.375
when they don't see
the point, or don't

00:19:38.375 --> 00:19:40.830
see them using it later.

00:19:40.830 --> 00:19:42.497
It's not necessarily
a definition of it.

00:19:42.497 --> 00:19:43.496
PROFESSOR: Right, right.

00:19:43.496 --> 00:19:45.060
No, but that's a
very good point.

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:48.240
And somebody had quoted
this idea of an app,

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:51.870
that if an app doesn't load in
something like seven seconds,

00:19:51.870 --> 00:19:54.114
people stop using it.

00:19:54.114 --> 00:19:56.280
Like if you try to get an
app to open on your phone,

00:19:56.280 --> 00:19:57.900
and you're like,
what's going on here?

00:19:57.900 --> 00:19:58.890
Come on, 1, 2, 3, 4--

00:19:58.890 --> 00:20:01.390
OK, forget it.

00:20:01.390 --> 00:20:05.160
And that's a similar idea,
that if it doesn't look

00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:07.050
like it's going to help you--

00:20:07.050 --> 00:20:10.636
and whatever that means,
help, it's self-defined, help.

00:20:10.636 --> 00:20:12.760
But if it doesn't look like
it's going to help you,

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:15.720
you're not going to buy into it.

00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:17.365
Some other thoughts
about this list?

00:20:34.580 --> 00:20:37.610
Personally, I don't
think that to be

00:20:37.610 --> 00:20:39.830
an educational
technology it has meet

00:20:39.830 --> 00:20:42.890
all these criteria at once.

00:20:42.890 --> 00:20:44.720
That's an important
thing to note,

00:20:44.720 --> 00:20:49.730
that it might
improve productivity.

00:20:49.730 --> 00:20:52.400
The old school learning
management systems

00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:56.780
that you put up problem
sets, and you put up--

00:20:56.780 --> 00:20:59.360
the grade book was in one
place, and that kind of thing.

00:20:59.360 --> 00:21:00.950
That might help
your productivity.

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:02.660
You're not looking
around for stuff.

00:21:02.660 --> 00:21:05.270
But it's not
necessarily promoting

00:21:05.270 --> 00:21:06.770
learning at any level.

00:21:06.770 --> 00:21:09.050
It's a delivery system, a
materials delivery system.

00:21:09.050 --> 00:21:10.670
So it kind of does this.

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:12.320
And it does this.

00:21:12.320 --> 00:21:16.400
But it might not really be part
of the learning enterprise.

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:17.000
It's a store.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:18.290
It's a repository.

00:21:18.290 --> 00:21:19.370
And that's fine.

00:21:19.370 --> 00:21:20.870
There's nothing wrong with that.

00:21:20.870 --> 00:21:23.630
But that's one type.

00:21:23.630 --> 00:21:27.590
If you're saying that it
enables communication,

00:21:27.590 --> 00:21:29.180
well, that might
be part of this.

00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:31.610
But it might be something else.

00:21:31.610 --> 00:21:35.181
If I say, all
right, it's a wiki.

00:21:35.181 --> 00:21:37.430
And I want you guys to read
what everybody else wrote,

00:21:37.430 --> 00:21:39.230
and to make a comment
on at least one other

00:21:39.230 --> 00:21:43.280
persons' posting, well, I
have facilitated communication

00:21:43.280 --> 00:21:46.130
between you in an
asynchronous way.

00:21:46.130 --> 00:21:52.100
I didn't tell everybody to do it
at noon on the 29th of October.

00:21:52.100 --> 00:21:55.858
But it does facilitate
communication.

00:21:58.410 --> 00:22:00.846
I think this one is a
loaded one, for sure.

00:22:00.846 --> 00:22:02.220
And it gets to
Michelle's comment

00:22:02.220 --> 00:22:06.240
about if you did it
right, it would do that.

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:11.200
But if you did it wrong, it's
likely to not do that at all.

00:22:14.280 --> 00:22:18.980
So these are attributes that
you could use to describe

00:22:18.980 --> 00:22:21.366
some educational technologies.

00:22:21.366 --> 00:22:23.240
I do have a definition
from the reading book.

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:28.370
But before I put that up, any
other thing you want to add?

00:22:28.370 --> 00:22:30.320
It's interesting
to think about it,

00:22:30.320 --> 00:22:32.340
like does it have
to be electronic?

00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:33.731
So I have had
classes in the past

00:22:33.731 --> 00:22:35.480
where people argue,
OK, well, a blackboard

00:22:35.480 --> 00:22:39.050
is an educational technology.

00:22:39.050 --> 00:22:42.050
I mean, you could do
that without some sort

00:22:42.050 --> 00:22:45.230
of human-made product.

00:22:45.230 --> 00:22:47.540
And without it, I would
have to be walking

00:22:47.540 --> 00:22:50.990
around speaking very slowly
and hoping you took notes,

00:22:50.990 --> 00:22:53.060
or walking around with--

00:22:53.060 --> 00:22:55.490
I don't know-- a piece
of paper that I wrote on,

00:22:55.490 --> 00:22:57.200
and sharing it with
you or something.

00:22:57.200 --> 00:23:02.960
So a blackboard does fit a lot
of these categories, right?

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:05.840
It's an efficient
delivery system.

00:23:05.840 --> 00:23:08.900
At some level, it
enables communication.

00:23:08.900 --> 00:23:14.060
It's a distribution
of learning materials.

00:23:14.060 --> 00:23:17.690
So we want to think
about whether it

00:23:17.690 --> 00:23:19.446
means it has to be electronic.

00:23:21.755 --> 00:23:23.630
And you may have guessed
by now, there is not

00:23:23.630 --> 00:23:27.680
a single definition, so
that's the other issue.

00:23:27.680 --> 00:23:28.460
Comments?

00:23:28.460 --> 00:23:29.129
Yes, go ahead.

00:23:29.129 --> 00:23:30.170
AUDIENCE: Just a comment.

00:23:30.170 --> 00:23:36.010
What about if it's not
well-moderated [INAUDIBLE]?

00:23:38.570 --> 00:23:41.660
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's
the efficient one,

00:23:41.660 --> 00:23:45.740
that we've all gotten
sucked into websites,

00:23:45.740 --> 00:23:48.920
or sucked into, perhaps,
an online discussion,

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:51.930
or commenting on something.

00:23:51.930 --> 00:23:54.710
And it might be interesting.

00:23:54.710 --> 00:23:56.260
You might learn.

00:23:56.260 --> 00:24:00.200
But it may not be
efficient at all.

00:24:00.200 --> 00:24:05.510
Or you might just be on
the screed end of things,

00:24:05.510 --> 00:24:08.540
where people are
just either ranting

00:24:08.540 --> 00:24:13.130
or they're reinforcing
misconceptions or whatever.

00:24:13.130 --> 00:24:15.572
So yeah, you do
have to kind of make

00:24:15.572 --> 00:24:17.030
sure people are
using it carefully.

00:24:17.030 --> 00:24:20.150
But that's true for
virtually anything you do.

00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:24.774
Any other comments?

00:24:24.774 --> 00:24:32.000
AUDIENCE: And I think, as well,
that the fact that these tools

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:33.860
are valuable.

00:24:33.860 --> 00:24:40.366
A student can decide to
stay home in the bad weather

00:24:40.366 --> 00:24:43.210
since he knows
this is available.

00:24:43.210 --> 00:24:45.202
Then he can go [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:48.010 --> 00:24:52.470
That could be good and bad.

00:24:52.470 --> 00:24:58.366
Because the student would
continue to learn on his own

00:24:58.366 --> 00:25:00.376
and become a good student.

00:25:00.376 --> 00:25:05.650
And then he could miss out on
some critical points as well.

00:25:05.650 --> 00:25:07.950
PROFESSOR: Right, right.

00:25:07.950 --> 00:25:15.880
But that implies some sort
of like web-housed delivered

00:25:15.880 --> 00:25:22.450
repository of content, or of
video lectures, or whatever.

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:29.150
You could have a course that
used clickers, let's say,

00:25:29.150 --> 00:25:32.860
that didn't even have a
website, but they used clickers.

00:25:32.860 --> 00:25:37.060
So that course might be using
educational technology, maybe

00:25:37.060 --> 00:25:40.281
in a very, very good
way in the classroom,

00:25:40.281 --> 00:25:42.030
but they don't even
bother with a website.

00:25:42.030 --> 00:25:45.300
So in that case, the
student has to come to class

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:49.230
if they want to experience that
particular use of technology.

00:25:49.230 --> 00:25:51.600
I think you're right, that
if you do have a website,

00:25:51.600 --> 00:25:55.080
or you do have lectures online,
or you do have rich content

00:25:55.080 --> 00:25:59.610
online, then it does
sort of, perhaps,

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:03.990
make being in the classroom
a little bit less necessary.

00:26:03.990 --> 00:26:07.920
I will say, if you employ active
learning methods in class,

00:26:07.920 --> 00:26:12.210
group discussions, et cetera,
that being in the classroom

00:26:12.210 --> 00:26:15.960
is, certainly, I would argue,
is value added for the student.

00:26:15.960 --> 00:26:19.200
So it's not a
replacement experience,

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:22.610
but it might be better
than nothing, let's say.

00:26:22.610 --> 00:26:24.710
It might not.

00:26:24.710 --> 00:26:26.018
Yes, Gordon.

00:26:26.018 --> 00:26:28.358
AUDIENCE: I found something
written very interesting

00:26:28.358 --> 00:26:34.240
when it said that if
you use clickers--

00:26:34.240 --> 00:26:36.316
I would love to do that.

00:26:36.316 --> 00:26:39.210
To take attendance
of the students,

00:26:39.210 --> 00:26:43.790
that it might [INAUDIBLE] the
students from using technology.

00:26:43.790 --> 00:26:47.530
But it's only [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:47.530 --> 00:26:49.590
It might actually be
good to have technology

00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:54.626
they can use non-evasively
to find out if the student is

00:26:54.626 --> 00:26:56.000
actually coming to your class.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:58.416
AUDIENCE: What if they gave
their clicker to their friend?

00:26:58.416 --> 00:27:00.622
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it's true.

00:27:00.622 --> 00:27:03.080
AUDIENCE: One person will come
with five friend's clickers,

00:27:03.080 --> 00:27:04.600
the clicker won't--

00:27:04.600 --> 00:27:08.214
AUDIENCE: If you have like
RFIB technology or something

00:27:08.214 --> 00:27:13.064
like that that can use to
[INAUDIBLE] come to the class

00:27:13.064 --> 00:27:19.240
to know that, OK, this person
is the one using [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:19.240 --> 00:27:22.650
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:27:22.650 --> 00:27:39.960
[INAUDIBLE]

00:27:39.960 --> 00:27:42.130
AUDIENCE: So in certain
courses you have to do that.

00:27:42.130 --> 00:27:43.070
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
you must do that.

00:27:43.070 --> 00:27:44.320
AUDIENCE: You have to show up?

00:27:44.320 --> 00:27:45.825
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
you should show up.

00:27:45.825 --> 00:27:49.610
But if you decide it's
difficult to take attendance,

00:27:49.610 --> 00:27:53.370
and if you have this wonderful
way of getting the students to

00:27:53.370 --> 00:27:54.360
[INAUDIBLE].

00:27:59.310 --> 00:28:09.370
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:09.370 --> 00:28:12.544
PROFESSOR: Well, I don't know
if there's an answer to that.

00:28:12.544 --> 00:28:14.210
For some students,
it's never a problem.

00:28:14.210 --> 00:28:15.610
For some students, it's awesome.

00:28:15.610 --> 00:28:18.190
For some students, it's
just more information.

00:28:18.190 --> 00:28:19.510
And it's just another path.

00:28:19.510 --> 00:28:20.110
And they're learning.

00:28:20.110 --> 00:28:20.620
And they're learning.

00:28:20.620 --> 00:28:21.130
And they're learning.

00:28:21.130 --> 00:28:23.546
And it's supplementing what
they're learning in the class.

00:28:25.870 --> 00:28:26.982
It kind of depends on--

00:28:26.982 --> 00:28:30.885
AUDIENCE: Taking attendance
that Gordon is talking about,

00:28:30.885 --> 00:28:31.814
so is it [INAUDIBLE]?

00:28:31.814 --> 00:28:32.730
PROFESSOR: Well, yeah.

00:28:32.730 --> 00:28:36.850
And actually that's
an important point

00:28:36.850 --> 00:28:39.400
